TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");
Context()->flags->set(useBaseTenLog=>1);

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,28,2);
$base = random(3,7,2);
$b = $base**(-1);
$r = $b-1;
$k = round(log($b)/log(exp(1))*1000)/1000;

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
Give the growth factor \(b\), the starting value \(a\), the growth rate \(r\), and the value of \(k\) when \(Q\) is written in the form \(Q = ae^{kt}\). If there is exponential is decay, then your growth rate should negative.
For help entering logarithms, see \{ AnswerFormatHelp("logarithms") \}
$PAR
\( Q = $a \cdot $base^{-t} \) has:
$PAR
\( b = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( a = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( r = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
$BR
\( k = \) \{ ans_rule(20) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS(Real("$b")->cmp() );
ANS(Real("$a")->cmp() );
ANS(Real("$r")->cmp() );
ANS(Real("ln($b)")->cmp() );

#ANS(num_cmp($a) );
#ANS(num_cmp($k,tol=>0.0006) );

$basem1 = $base - 1;

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$PAR
We have
\( Q = $a \cdot $base^{-t} = $a\,(1/$base)^t = $a\,e^{\ln(1/$base)\,t} \).
Thus
\(b = 1/$base\),
\(a = $a\),
\(r = b - 1 = \frac1{$base} - 1 = -\frac{$basem1}{$base}\), and
\(k = \ln b = \ln(\frac1{$base})\).

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

